B. cinerea
(teleomorph: 
Botryotinia fuckeliana
)

is the causal agent of grey mold disease that affects a total of 586 genera of vascular plants, representing over 1400 ornamental and agriculturally important plant species (

; 

). This fungus is a typical necrotroph whose infective cycle includes the killing of plant cells, maceration of plant tissue and then reproduction by forming asexual spores on the decomposing plant material. Throughout the infection, 

B. cinerea

uses a battery of phytotoxins, enzymes, and reactive oxygen species (

