The biosynthetic route and the polyketide synthases involved in the biosynthesis of botcinin and its derivatives and botrylactones (compounds 
2–6
) have been described in the literature (

; 

). Biosynthesis was studied by using acetate and malonate units labelled with deuterium and carbon thirteen. It has been shown that the condensation of an acetate starter unit and four molecules of malonate yields a pentaketide (C10), with its four pendent methyl group originating from L-methylmethionine. The pentaketide losses the starter unit of the acetate to give botcinic and botcineric acid derivatives and their relatives botcinins (

).

Moreover, the botrydial biosynthetic cluster consists of seven genes codifying for one sesquiterpene cyclase BcBOT2, three P450 monooxygenases, BcBOT1, BcBOT3 and BcBOT4, one acetyl transferase BcBOT5, one dehydrogenases BcBOT7, and the putative Zn(II) 
2
Cys 
6
transcription factor BcBOT6 (

; 

). The gene 
BcBOT4
encodes a cytochrome P450 monooxygenase that was shown to catalyse regio- and stereospecific hydroxylation at position C-4 of the presilphiperfolan-8-β- ol skeleton (

). The null mutant 

bcbot4
Δ

abolished the production of botrydial and its derivatives, and instead accumulated the tricyclic presilphiperfolane alcohol and overproduced a significant number of polyketides (

; 

).

As expected, the null mutant accumulated the tricyclic presilphiperfolane-8β- ol, the key intermediate in botrydial biosynthesis (

; 

; 

). In addition to known polyketides previously reported, (

, 

; 

