, were obtained and their structures were characterized by extensive mono- and bidimensional NMR experiments.

The 1 H-NMR spectrum of compound 21 showed characteristic signals of the basic bicyclic skeleton of botcinin and signals corresponding to the side chain at C-7 were clearly missing. Thus, three signal doublets at δ 1.10, 1.20, 1.22, and one singlet (δ 1.22), integrating three protons each, were assigned to the four methyl groups on carbons C-2, C-6, C-8 and C-4, respectively. Two signals, one at δ 3.1 (dq, J = 10, 7.0 Hz) and another at δ 2.0 (m), were assigned to protons H-2, and H-6 respectively. Also, four signals characteristic of protons germinal to oxygenated function at δ 3.50 (dq, J = 9.7, 6.4 Hz), 3.7 (d, J = 11 Hz), 2.9 (t, J = 10 Hz), 5.4 (d, J = 9.7 Hz), were assigned to protons H-8, H-5, H-7 and H-3. Lastly, a singlet at δ 2.1 corresponded to the methyl of the acetate group on carbon C-3. Spectroscopic constants were consistent with structure 21 ( Fig. 2 ), corresponding to the compound obtained from hydrogenation of the double bond in the side chain of botcinin A ( 4 ), and subsequent acid hydrolysis (HCl, 12 M) to remove the acyl portion (
). The absolute configuration of 21 has been reported (
). This is the first time that this compound has been isolated and we have named it botcinin H.

Compounds 22–24 displayed a pattern of NMR signals characteristic of botcinins (
,
). The 13 C-NMR for compound 22 contained 20 signals which, considered jointly with the HRMS, were consistent with the molecular formula C 20 H 30 O 7 . These data, and the absence of NMR spectra signals corresponding to the acetyl group at C-3, indicated a side chain containing eight carbon atoms.

The botcinins and botrylactones, compounds 2–6 and those described in this article 21–23 , are polyketides biosynthesized by sequential assembly of a per-methylated pentaketide (C10) arising from the condensation of an acetate primer unit and four malonate molecules, leading to a botrylactone-like intermediate ( 27 ) yielding botrylactone ( 6 ) or botcinin derivatives 2–5, through “a” route, Fig. 3 , (
). Preliminary isotopic labelling experiments in which labelled sodium acetates, propionate and S-methylmethionine were fed to
B. cinerea
cultures, clearly demonstrate that botcinin skeleton arise from an acetate-derived polyketide assembled from carbon C-8 to C-1, with its four pendent methyl groups originating from S -adenosylmethylmethionine (
).

These polyketides require the action of two polyketide synthases (PKS), BcBoa6 and BcBoa9 ( Fig. 3 ). Deletion of either the bcboa6 or bcboa9 gene (
) showed that they act in concert to synthetize botcinic acid ( 2 ):
Δ bcboa6
and
Δ bcboa9
null mutants did not produce botcinic acid or its derivatives; interestingly
Δ bcboa9
overproduced botrylactone ( 6 ) (
;
;
).

Further isotopic labelling experiments showed that BcBoa6 mediates the formation of the pentaketide core, common to both botcinins and botrylactones, whereas BcBoa9 is responsible for the 7- O -acyltetraketide side chain of botcinic acid and its derivatives 2–4 (
;
). These results enabled us to propose the biosynthetic route showed in Fig. 3 , where the acetate starter unit in botcinins is lost through a retro-Claisen type C–C bond cleavage of the botrylactone-like precursor 26 . The starter unit remaining attached at position C-3 of the botcinin molecule. Therefore, the 3- O -acetyl group in botcinins (4, 5 ) and 3-acetylbotcinic acid ( 29 ) is derived from the starter unit of the botrylactone precursors 26 and 27 ( Fig. 3 ) (
;
).

Interestingly, the basic structure of cinbotolide of this compound corresponds with the same basic tetraketide of botcinins, which should be cyclized in different positions. Thus, attack of a hydroxyl group at C-5 to a keto group at C-8 would give ring B, followed by the simultaneous lactonization with the hydroxyl at C-4 to yield 
25
. Stereochemistry was then assigned on the basis of the absolute configuration previously assigned to the polyketides of botcinins (

) and cinbotolide A (

) and additional nOe experiments.

